  "prompt": "What are records made of?",
  "response": "Records, particularly vinyl records, are primarily made of a few key materials:\n\n1. **Polyvinyl Chloride (PVC)**: This is the most common material used for pressing vinyl records. PVC is a type of plastic that is durable and can be molded into the shape of a record.\n\n2. **Release Agents**: These are sometimes applied to the metal plates used in the pressing process to ensure that the records can be easily removed from the molds after they are formed.\n\n3. **Additives**: Various additives may be mixed with the PVC to enhance properties such as flexibility, durability, and the ability to hold sound quality.\n\nThe production process involves heating the PVC and molding it into the shape of the record, which includes the grooves that encode the audio. Once pressed, the surface may be treated or coated to improve playback quality and durability.\n\nIn addition to vinyl records, other types of records (like shellac records or modern digital records) may be made from different materials, but vinyl has become the most notable and widely used material for records since the 1940s.",
